DIV1.P:
The means and methods which God makes use of, in calling forth his ministers, are exceeding va∣rious; so that no exact steps can be described by us, for his calling forth his ministers, any more than for his calling souls into the kingdom of his grace. But the teaching of the Spirit of God in his word, a view of the worth of souls and of the present state of things among the people, with the command of Christ to preach his gospel to them, is the essence of an internal call into that great work. The external call is by his church, who are invested with authority from Christ to carry all his laws into execution in his name. For, after warning believers of the danger, of being spoiled through philosophy and vain deceit, by men who do not hold THE HEAD, he says, Let the word of Christ dwell in you richly in all wisdom; teaching and admonishing one another in psalms, and hymns, and spiritual songs, singing with grace in your hearts to the Lord. And whatsoever ye do in word or deed, do all in the name of the Lord Jesus, giv∣ing thanks to God and the Father by him. Col. ii. 8—10, 18—23. iii. 16, 17. In the last of these chapters he says, Covetousness is idolatry. And in another place he says, No whoremonger, nor un∣clean person, nor covetous man who is an idolater, hath any inheritance in the kingdom of Christ, and of God. Eph. v. 5. And such have ever had a great influence in all national churches, by whom all wars have been managed. But when the house of God, which is his church, shall be established upon his revealed will, above all the powers of this

world, bloody wars will come to an end. And believers will say, All people will walk every one in the name of his god, and we will walk in the name of the Lord our God forever and ever. Micah iv. 1—5. The saints of the Most High shall take the kingdom, and possess the kingdom forever, even forever and ever. Dan. vii. 18. For, though the devil will deceive multitudes, after the reign of the saints for a thou∣sand years, yet their complete destruction will pre∣vent any interruption of the kingdom of the saints. Rev. xx. 7—9. All men desire safety and happi∣ness, and no men would disobey the revealed will of God, if they were not deceived. Titus iii. 3. Evil men and seducers shall wax worse and worse, deceiving, and being deceived. 2 Tim. iii. 13. No men would deceive others, if they were not first deceived themselves. And Christ says, If it were possible, they shall deceive the very elect. Mat. xxiv. 24. And multitudes are now so much deceived, as to deny that God has an elect number among mankind, distinct from the rest. But the apostle Peter writes to the saints, and calls them the Elect according to the foreknowledge of God the Father, through sanctification of the Spirit unto obedience, and sprinkling of the blood of Iesus Christ. And to them he says, The elders which are among you I exhort, who am also an elder, and a witness of the suffer∣ings of Christ, and also a partaker of the glory that shall be revealed; feed the flock of God which is among you, taking the oversight thereof, not by constraint, but willingly; not for filthy lucre, but of a ready mind; neither as being lords over God's heritage, but being ensamples of the flock. And when the chief Shepherd shall appear, ye shall re∣ceive a crown of glory that fadeth not away. Like∣wise ye younger, submit yourselves unto the elder;

yea, all of you be subject one to and be clothed with humility: for God resisteth the proud, and giveth grace unto the humble. 1 Peter i. 2. v. 1—5.
